  "topic": "How to manage and dealing with fake content on social media.",
  "opinion": "As a 73-year-old man living in Washington DC, I've seen a lot change over the years, and social media is one of those things that's both a blessing and a curse. I spend several hours daily on social media, mostly to stay connected with my two children and to pass the time since I'm unemployed and divorced, which often leaves me feeling depressed. Being agnostic, I don't rely on faith to guide me, so I have to be extra careful about what I believe online. My education level is only lower secondary, and my parents had vocational and bachelor's degrees, so I never got far in school, but I've learned to be very conscientious—my OCEAN score shows I'm high in conscientiousness at 100, which means I'm organized and thorough. That helps me deal with fake content. First, I always check the source of any information I see. If it's from a news outlet I've never heard of or looks sketchy, I ignore it. I also look for multiple sources saying the same thing before I believe it. Since I'm low in openness with a score of 17, I'm not quick to try new things or trust unfamiliar ideas, so I stick to what I know works. My hobbies like yoga, board games, and painting keep me grounded, and I apply that patience to social media too—I don't rush to share or react to posts. I've seen too many people get upset over fake news, and with my low neuroticism score of 2, I stay calm and avoid getting stressed. I'm also low in agreeableness at 23, so I don't feel pressured to go along with what others say; I make my own judgments. To manage fake content, I use simple tools like fact-checking websites and report suspicious posts to the platforms. It's not perfect, but being a native-born American, I value truth and responsibility. In short, I handle fake content by being cautious, double-checking everything, and not letting it affect my mood, even with my depression.",
